      <!-- Slide 1: What is Pachamanca -->
      <div class="slide">
        <h2 class="slide-title">What is Pachamanca?</h2>
        <div class="slide-content">
          <p>Pachamanca is an ancient Peruvian cooking method that dates back to pre-Columbian times, when the Incas lived in this region. The word "Pachamanca" comes from Quechua (an indigenous language) and means "pot of the earth."</p>
          <div class="slide-image-container">
            <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9d/Pachamanca_Peru.JPG/640px-Pachamanca_Peru.JPG" alt="Traditional Pachamanca meal being uncovered from the earth" class="slide-image">
          <p class="image-attribution">Image source: <em>Pachamanca Peru.JPG</em>, Javi270270, Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 3.0, via Wikimedia Commons.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <!-- Slide 2: How It Works -->
      <div class="slide">
        <h2 class="slide-title">How Pachamanca Works</h2>
        <div class="slide-content">
          <div class="step">
            <span class="step-number">1</span>
            <span class="step-text">People dig a hole in the ground</span>
          </div>
          <div class="step">
            <span class="step-number">2</span>
            <span class="step-text">They heat stones over fire until they're very hot</span>
          </div>
          <div class="step">
            <span class="step-number">3</span>
            <span class="step-text">They place the hot stones in the hole</span>
          </div>
          <div class="slide-image-container">
            <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9e/Tradiciones_Familiares_por_Fiestas_patrias.jpg/640px-Tradiciones_Familiares_por_Fiestas_patrias.jpg" alt="Heating stones for Pachamanca" class="slide-image">
          <p class="image-attribution">Image source: <em>Tradiciones Familiares por Fiestas Patrias.jpg</em>, Georgina Belen Vega C., Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 4.0, via Wikimedia Commons.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <!-- Slide 3: How It Works (continued) -->
      <div class="slide">
        <h2 class="slide-title">How Pachamanca Works</h2>
        <div class="slide-content">
          <div class="step">
            <span class="step-number">4</span>
            <span class="step-text">They layer different foods on top of the stones (meats, potatoes, corn)</span>
          </div>
          <div class="step">
            <span class="step-number">5</span>
            <span class="step-text">Everything is covered with more hot stones, leaves, and earth</span>
          </div>
          <div class="step">
            <span class="step-number">6</span>
            <span class="step-text">The food cooks slowly underground, creating amazing flavors!</span>
          </div>
          <div class="slide-image-container">
